            <msItem>
              <author key="lccn:n82097778" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/31996761">
                <persName xml:lang="ara-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Ghazzālī, 1058-1111</persName>
                <persName xml:lang="ara">طبرى</persName>
                <note>Born in <name type="place" key="lccn:nr96034543">Ṭūs (Iran)</name>, he rew
                  up as an orphan togheter with a younger brother. At a young age, he studied
                  Islamic jurisprudence in <name type="place" key="lccn:nr98000765">Gurgān
                    (Gulistān, Iran). </name>, before moving to <name type="place"
                    key="lccn:n81144037">Nīshāpūr (Iran)</name> to become a disciple of the
                  famous theologian and jurist <persName key="lccn:n 82164819‏"
                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/19728485" xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" type="alt">ʻAbd
                    al-Malik Juwaynī, d. 1085</persName>. In that city, he also joined a group of
                  Sufis and later travelled to the Seljuq court to join a group of scholars under
                  the patronage of the vizier <persName ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/46772622"
                    key="lccn:n85181862‏" type="standard" xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc">Niẓām al-Mulk,
                    1018-1092</persName>. In <date calendar="Hijri-qamari" when="1091">484</date>,
                  the vizier appointed <persName key="lccn:n82097778"
                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/31996761" xml:lang="ara-Latn-x-lc" type="standard"
                    >Ghazzālī, 1058-1111</persName> professor in Sha'afi jurisprudence at the <name
                    type="org">Neẓāmīya madrasa</name> in <name type="place" key="lccn:n80006292"
                    >Baghdad (Iraq)</name>. Partly due to the assasination of his patron <persName
                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/46772622" key="lccn:n85181862‏" type="standard"
                    xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc">Niẓām al-Mulk, 1018-1092</persName> and partly because
                  of a personal crisis, in <date calendar="Hijri-qamari" when="1095">488</date> he
                  used the excuse of a trip to <name type="place" key="lccn:n79032243">Mecca</name>
                  to give up his academic career. It is uncertain what did <persName
                    key="lccn:n82097778" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/31996761"
                    xml:lang="ara-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Ghazzālī, 1058-1111</persName> do
                  during the following 11 years. Apparently, he visited <name type="place"
                    key="lccn:n79143055">Damascus (Syria)</name>, <name type="place"
                    key="lccn:n81126877">Jerusalem</name>. <name type="place" key="lccn:n80061791"
                    >Egypt</name>, <name type="place" key="lccn:n80006292">Baghdad (Iraq)</name> and
                  finally settled in his hometown of <name type="place" key="lccn:nr96034543">Ṭūs
                    (Iran)</name>. CONTINUE]</note>
              </author>
              <title xml:lang="ara-Latn-x-lc">Kīmiyā-yi saʻādat̄</title>
              <title xml:lang="ara">کيمياى سعادت</title>
              <note>A work on Islamic theology with an emphasis on self-discipline, asceticism and
                mysticism. This is a Persian abbreviation of the Arabic <title
                  xml:lang="ara-Latn-x-lc">Iḥyāʼ ʻulūm al-dīn (<foreign xml:lang="ara">إحياء
                    علوم الدين</foreign>)</title> by the same author. This work was written for his
                disciples aiming to prove that the Sufi life is compatible with the shari'a. The
                author attempts to reconcile both Sufism and Shari'a to argue against certain Sufi
                circles that were advocating for neglecting the duties of ordinary Muslims.</note>
              <note corresp="composition">Compossed <date calendar="Hijri-qamari" notAfter="1105"
                  >Not after 499</date></note>
